===活動組織===
{{TransH}}
[[File:Working_New_Years_Eve_Social_Media_for_NBC_(9234114888).jpg|thumb]]
[[File:US_Navy_061231-N-6897L-030_Electrician's_Mate_2nd_Class_Oswaldo_San_Andres_and_Master-at-Arms_2nd_Class_Lillianne_Perez_join_New_York_City_Mayor_Michael_R._Bloomberg.jpg|thumb]] members ceremonially activating the drop for 2007.]]

To facilitate the arrival of attendees, Times Square is closed to traffic beginning in the late afternoon on New Year's Eve. The square is then divided into different viewing sections referred to as "pens", into which attendees are directed sequentially upon arrival.<ref name=cnn-07ball/><ref name=cnn-security2011>{{cite news|title=New Year's Eve security main focus for NYPD|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/12/29/us/new-york-times-square/|work=CNN|access-date=2013-11-09|date=2011-12-30|archive-date=2022-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220417080406/https://www.cnn.com/2011/12/29/us/new-york-times-square/}}</ref> Security is strictly enforced by the [[New_York_City_Police_Department|New York City Police Department]] (NYPD), even more so since the 2001–02 edition in the wake of the [[September_11_attacks|September 11 attacks]]. Attendees are required to pass through [[security_checkpoint|security checkpoint]]s before they are assigned a pen, and are prohibited from bringing backpacks or alcohol to the event.<ref name=cnn-security2011 />

Security was increased further for its 2017–18 edition due to recent incidents such as the [[2017_New_York_City_truck_attack|truck attack in New York on October 31]], and the [[2017_Las_Vegas_shooting|2017 Las Vegas shooting]]; these included additional patrols of Times Square hotels, rooftop patrol squads and counter-snipers, and the installation of reflective markers on buildings to help officers identify the location of elevated shooters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/28/nyregion/times-square-new-years-eve-security.html|title=In Wake of Attacks, Tighter Security for Times Square on New Year's Eve|last=Mueller|first=Benjamin|date=2017-12-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=2022-06-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220615235032/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/28/nyregion/times-square-new-years-eve-security.html}}</ref> For 2018–19, the NYPD announced its intent to use a camera-equipped [[quadcopter|quadcopter]] to augment the over 1,200 fixed cameras monitoring Times Square, but it was left grounded due to inclement weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2018/12/31/nypds-latest-tool-keeping-times-square-revelers-safe-remote-controlled-drone/|title=The NYPD planned to use drones during Times Square New Year's Eve celebration. Then it started raining.|last=Holley|first=Peter|website=[[The_Washington_Post|The Washington Post]]|date=2018-12-31|access-date=2019-01-03|archive-date=2021-01-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125231500/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2018/12/31/nypds-latest-tool-keeping-times-square-revelers-safe-remote-controlled-drone/}}</ref>

