Festivities formally begin in the early evening, with an opening ceremony featuring the raising of the ball at 6:00 p.m [[Eastern_Time|E]]T.<ref name=cnn-07ball/> [[Party_favor|Party favor]]s are distributed to attendees, which have historically included large balloons, hats, and other items branded with the event's corporate sponsors.<ref name=nyt-nivea>{{cite news|title=For New Year's Eve, the Tie-Ins Erupt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/14/business/media/14adco.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|access-date=2013-11-10|date=2010-12-13|archive-date=2021-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211125094008/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/14/business/media/14adco.html?_r=0}}</ref><ref name=time-veryconfetti/> The lead-up to midnight features a program of entertainment, including musical performances: some of these performances are organized by, and aired by [[#Broadcasting|New Year's Eve television specials]] broadcasting from Times Square.<ref name=time-veryconfetti>{{cite news|title=A Very Confetti New Year's|url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1573429,00.html|work=Time|access-date=2013-11-10|date=2007-01-02|archive-date=2021-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210417073419/http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1573429,00.html}}</ref><ref name=usatoday-etheridge/>

The climax of the festivities is the drop itself, which begins at 11:59:00 p.m. ET.<ref name=cnn-07ball/> Officially, the drop is activated using a button inside a special control room within One Times Square, synchronized using an [[National_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology|National Institute of Standards and Technology]] (NIST) [[time_signal|time signal]] received via satellite.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|last=Bousquette|first=Isabelle|date=2021-12-30|title=The New Year’s Eve Ball Will Drop, Covid or Not, if John Trowbridge Has His Way|language=en-US|work=Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-years-eve-times-square-ball-drop-covid-11640886781|access-date=2021-12-30|issn=0099-9660|archive-date=2022-06-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220611032253/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-years-eve-times-square-ball-drop-covid-11640886781}}</ref><ref name="ny1-smoothly">{{cite news|last=Balkin|first=Adam|date=2003-12-30|title=Technology Helps Times Square New Year's Eve Ball Drop Run Smoothly|newspaper=[[NY1|NY1]]|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/36078/technology-helps-times-square-new-year-s-eve-ball-drop-run-smoothly|url-status=dead|access-date=2012-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609094110/http://www.ny1.com/content/36078/technology-helps-times-square-new-year-s-eve-ball-drop-run-smoothly|archive-date=2013-06-09}}</ref> Since 1996, the drop has been ceremonially "activated" on-stage by one or more special guests, joined by the current [[mayor_of_New_York_City|mayor of New York City]], by pressing a button on a smaller model of the ball.<ref name=nyc-9697guest>{{cite web|title=Mayor Giuliani Announces New Tradition for New Year's Eve: Community Hero to Lead Times Square Celebration|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/html/96/sp685-96.html|publisher=City of New York|access-date=2012-12-19|archive-date=2022-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220416090319/http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/html/96/sp685-96.html}}</ref> The guests are selected annually  to recognize their community involvement or significance, and have included:
