The second ball was last used for the 1954-55 event in favor of a third design; which was now 6 feet in diameter, constructed from aluminum, and weighed {{convert|150|lb|kg}}.<ref name="crump"/> The first [[countdown|countdown]] to midnight occurred in 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/12/31/1069538912/americans-didnt-count-down-the-new-year-until-the-1970s |title=Americans didn't count down the new year until the 1970s |date=2021-12-31 |publisher=[[NPR|NPR]] |access-date=2022-01-25 |archive-date=2022-02-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220202212849/https://www.npr.org/2021/12/31/1069538912/americans-didnt-count-down-the-new-year-until-the-1970s }}</ref>

For the 1981-82 event, the ball was modified to make it resemble an apple with red bulbs and a green "stem", alluding to New York's nickname, "[[Big_Apple|the Big Apple]]".<ref name="nyt-deconstructed" /> For the 1987-88 event, organizers acknowledged the addition of a [[leap_second|leap second]] earlier that day (leap seconds are appended at midnight [[Coordinated_Universal_Time|UTC]], which is five hours before midnight in New York) by extending the drop to 61 seconds, and by including a special one-second light show during the extra second.<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert D. |last=McFadden |title='88 Countdown: 3, 2, 1, Leap Second, 0 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/29/nyregion/88-countdown-3-2-1-leap-second-0.html |work=[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]] |date=1987-12-31 |access-date=2009-01-02 |archive-date=2022-05-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528050233/https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/29/nyregion/88-countdown-3-2-1-leap-second-0.html }}</ref> The original white bulbs returned to the ball for the 1988-89 event, but were replaced by red, white, and blue bulbs for the 1990-91 event to salute the troops of [[Operation_Desert_Shield_(Gulf_War)|Operation Desert Shield]].<ref name="nyt-deconstructed" />

The third ball was revamped again in 1995 for 1996, adding a computerized lighting system with 180 [[halogen_lamp|halogen bulbs]] and 144 [[strobe_light|strobe light]]s, and over 12,000 [[rhinestone|rhinestone]]s.<ref name="crump"/><ref name=nydn-biggerball>{{cite news|last=Sutton|first=Larry|title=Bigger Ball to Peg Square|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/brighter-ball-peg-square-article-1.703159|work=New York Daily News|access-date=2013-11-06|archive-date=2022-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424220824/https://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/brighter-ball-peg-square-article-1.703159}}</ref> Lighting designer Barry Arnold stated that the changes were "something [that] had to be done to make this event more spectacular as we approach the millennium."<ref name=nydn-biggerball/>

The drop itself became computerized through the use of an electric [[winch|winch]] synchronized with the [[National_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology|National Institute of Standards and Technology]]'s [[time_signal|time signal]]; the first drop with the new system was not without issues, however, as a glitch caused the ball to pause for a short moment halfway through its descent.<ref name=nyt-vault>{{cite news|title=When Party Is Over, the Ball Lands Here|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/31/nyregion/31vault.html|work=The New York Times|access-date=2013-01-15|first=James|last=Barron|date=2009-12-31|archive-date=2022-01-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125074649/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/31/nyregion/31vault.html}}</ref> The following year, John Trowbridge was hired as the drop's new technical director; in 2021, Jeff Strauss told ''[[The_Wall_Street_Journal|The Wall Street Journal]]'' that the drop has never had any technical issues since.<ref name=":3"/>

After its 44th use in 1999, the third ball was retired and placed on display at the Atlanta headquarters of Jamestown Group, owners of One Times Square.<ref name="nyt-deconstructed">{{cite news|title=Deconstructed – Times Square Ball – Lots of Sparkle for a Swift Fall|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/nyregion/27ball.html?ref=nyregion&gwh=DFA1FDC3A94D96DE864D020AB6405314|work=The New York Times|access-date=2013-01-15|first=Alan|last=Feuer|date=2009-12-27|archive-date=2021-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211125103445/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/nyregion/27ball.html?ref=nyregion&gwh=DFA1FDC3A94D96DE864D020AB6405314}}</ref>
