As a public event, the festivities and ball drop are often broadcast on television. A host [[Press_pool|pool feed]] is provided to broadcasters for use in coverage, which for 2016–17 consisted of 21 cameras.<ref name="tvtech-timessquare">{{cite web|title=Meet the Team Behind Times Square New Year's Eve|url=http://www.tvtechnology.com/news/0002/meet-the-team-behind-times-square-new-years-eve/280039|website=TV Technology|publisher=NewBay Media|access-date=2016-12-30|archive-date=2016-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230232113/http://www.tvtechnology.com/news/0002/meet-the-team-behind-times-square-new-years-eve/280039}}</ref> Since 2008–09, an official [[webcast|webcast]] of the ball drop and its associated festivities has been produced, streamed via [[Livestream.com|Livestream.com]].<ref name="tvtech-timessquare"/><ref name=nyt-balldroponline>{{cite news|last=Taub|first=Erica A.|title=New Year's Eve in Times Square Is Now a Webcast|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/24/technology/personaltech/24tsquare.html?_r=0|access-date=2012-12-06|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2009-12-24|archive-date=2022-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220423105719/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/24/technology/personaltech/24tsquare.html?_r=0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Extra-bright ball to drop at Times Square|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/news/2007-12-27-bright-ball-drop_N.htm|publisher=USA Today|access-date=2012-12-06|first=Jerry|last=Shriver|date=2007-12-27|archive-date=2018-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230103141/https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/news/2007-12-27-bright-ball-drop_N.htm}}</ref>

The event is covered as part of New Year's Eve [[television_special|television special]]s on several major U.S. television networks, which usually intersperse on-location coverage from Times Square with entertainment segments, such as musical performances (some of which held live in Times Square as part of the event). By far the most notable of these is ''[[Dick_Clark's_New_Year's_Rockin'_Eve|Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve]]''; created, produced, and originally hosted by the entertainer [[Dick_Clark|Dick Clark]] until his death in 2012 (with [[Regis_Philbin|Regis Philbin]] filling in for its 2004-05 broadcast), and currently hosted by [[Ryan_Seacrest|Ryan Seacrest]], the program first aired on [[National_Broadcasting_Company|NBC]] in 1972 before moving to [[American_Broadcasting_Company|ABC]], where it has been broadcast ever since.<ref name="2012Edition"/><ref name=fbny-making/> ''New Year's Rockin' Eve'' has consistently been the most-watched New Year's Eve special in the U.S. annually, peaking at 25.6 million viewers for its 2017–18 edition.<ref name="2018Ratings">{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2018/01/01/new-years-rockin-eve-ryan-seacrest-ratings-2017/ |title=Ratings: Ryan Seacrest's Rockin' Eve Hits All-Time Highs, Fox's Steve Harvey a Big Improvement Over Pitbull |last=Mitovich |first=Matt Webb |work=[[TVLine|TVLine]] |date=2018-01-01 |access-date=2018-01-02 |archive-date=2018-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101234838/https://tvline.com/2018/01/01/new-years-rockin-eve-ryan-seacrest-ratings-2017/ }}</ref><ref name="2012Edition">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/31/arts/television/dick-clark-and-rockin-eve-reach-milestone.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|title=4 Decades Later, He Still Counts|date=2011-12-31|access-date=2012-01-01|first=Brian|last=Stelter|newspaper=New York Times|page=C1|archive-date=2014-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327100735/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/31/arts/television/dick-clark-and-rockin-eve-reach-milestone.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print}}</ref><ref name=nyre2012-ratings>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|title=Nielsens: Clark's 'Rockin' Eve,' football start year well|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/story/2012-01-04/nielsen-ratings-dick-clark/52381476/1|publisher=USA Today|access-date=2012-11-30|date=2012-01-04|archive-date=2013-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921075547/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/story/2012-01-04/nielsen-ratings-dick-clark/52381476/1}}</ref> Following the death of Dick Clark in April 2012, a crystal engraved with his name was added to the 2013 ball in tribute.<ref name=fbny-making>{{cite web|last=Barmash|first=Jerry|title=Marking New Year's Eve at Times Square Without Dick Clark|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/marking-new-years-eve-at-times-square-without-dick-clark_b73011|publisher=FishbowlNY|access-date=2012-12-21|archive-date=2012-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121230201058/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/marking-new-years-eve-at-times-square-without-dick-clark_b73011}}</ref>

Across the remaining networks,  [[Fox_New_Year's_Eve_specials|Fox]] has occasionally broadcast its New Year's specials from Times Square.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Fox Swaps Pitbull for Steve Harvey on New Year's Eve|language=en|work=The Hollywood Reporter|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-swaps-pitbull-steve-harvey-new-years-eve-1059096|access-date=2017-11-18|archive-date=2021-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210426135914/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-swaps-pitbull-steve-harvey-new-years-eve-1059096}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=2020-12-02|title=Ken Jeong And Joel McHale To Ring In 2021 As Hosts Of Fox's New Year's Eve Special|url=https://deadline.com/2020/12/ken-jeong-joel-mchale-fox-new-years-eve-toast-roast-special-hosts-1234636292/|access-date=2020-12-29|website=[[Deadline_Hollywood|Deadline]]|archive-date=2020-12-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217035621/https://deadline.com/2020/12/ken-jeong-joel-mchale-fox-new-years-eve-toast-roast-special-hosts-1234636292/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Ryan|date=2020-12-02|title=Ken Jeong and Joel McHale to Host Fox's New Year's Eve Countdown Special, Replacing Steve Harvey|url=https://tvline.com/2020/12/02/ken-jeong-joel-mchale-fox-new-years-eve-countdown-special-2021/|access-date=2020-12-29|website=[[TVLine|TVLine]]|archive-date=2021-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211125102944/https://tvline.com/2020/12/02/ken-jeong-joel-mchale-fox-new-years-eve-countdown-special-2021/}}</ref> Spanish-language network [[Univision|Univision]] broadcasts ''[[Feliz!_(Univision_program)|¡Feliz!]]'', hosted by [[Raúl_de_Molina|Raúl de Molina]] of ''[[El_Gordo_y_La_Flaca|El Gordo y La Flaca]]''.<ref name=":2">{{cite news | url=http://www.bradenton.com/2011/12/31/3756320/ring-in-the-new-year-with-ryan.html | title=Ring in the new year with Ryan, Carson or Anderson | work=Bradenton Herald | access-date=2013-11-14 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214102536/http://www.bradenton.com/2011/12/31/3756320/ring-in-the-new-year-with-ryan.html | archive-date=2013-12-14 }}</ref><ref name=thr-foxpitbull15>{{cite web|title=Pitbull to Host New Year's Eve Live Show for Fox|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pitbull-host-new-years-eve-703133|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=2014-05-12|access-date=2014-12-19|archive-date=2021-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211211827/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pitbull-host-new-years-eve-703133}}</ref> On [[Cable_television|cable]], [[CNN|CNN]] carries coverage of the festivities, known as ''[[New_Year's_Eve_Live_(CNN_program)|New Year's Eve Live]]'', currently hosted by [[Anderson_Cooper|Anderson Cooper]] and [[Andy_Cohen_(television_personality)|Andy Cohen]] (the latter first replacing [[Kathy_Griffin|Kathy Griffin]] for 2018).<ref name="variety-andycohen">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cnn-new-year-anderson-cooper-andy-cohen-1202587221/|title=CNN Will Replace Kathy Griffin With Andy Cohen for New Year's Eve|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=2017-10-11|work=Variety|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US|archive-date=2017-11-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114201322/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cnn-new-year-anderson-cooper-andy-cohen-1202587221/}}</ref> [[Fox_News|Fox News]] carries ''All-American New Year'', which was most recently hosted by [[Elisabeth_Hasselbeck|Elisabeth Hasselbeck]] and [[Bill_Hemmer|Bill Hemmer]] from Times Square.<ref name="wp-mostentertaining">{{cite news|title=TV highlights: Networks compete for most entertaining New Year's show|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/tv-highlights-networks-compete-for-most-entertaining-new-years-show/2013/12/30/3826f0fa-715a-11e3-8def-a33011492df2_story.html|work=Washington Post|access-date=2013-12-31|date=2013-12-30|archive-date=2014-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216095405/http://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/tv-highlights-networks-compete-for-most-entertaining-new-years-show/2013/12/30/3826f0fa-715a-11e3-8def-a33011492df2_story.html}}</ref>
