Beginning in the 1940s, NBC broadcast coverage from Times Square anchored by [[Ben_Grauer|Ben Grauer]] on both radio and television. Its coverage was later incorporated into special episodes of ''[[The_Tonight_Show|The Tonight Show]]'', continuing through [[Johnny_Carson|Johnny Carson]] and [[Jay_Leno|Jay Leno]]'s tenures on the program. NBC would later introduce a dedicated special, ''[[New_Year's_Eve_with_Carson_Daly|New Year's Eve with Carson Daly]]'' (later renamed ''NBC's New Year's Eve''), hosted by former [[MTV|MTV]] personality [[Carson_Daly|Carson Daly]], which first began midnight coverage in 2006,<ref name="usatoday-battle">{{cite news|last=Oldenberg|first=Ann|title=Battle of Times Square|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-12-29-clark-nye-return_x.htm|work=USA Today|access-date=2013-01-05|date=2005-12-29|archive-date=2013-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110055047/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-12-29-clark-nye-return_x.htm}}</ref><ref name="usatoday-battle2">{{cite news|last=Oldenberg|first=Ann|date=2005-12-29|title=Battle of Times Square|publisher=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-12-29-clark-nye-return_x.htm|access-date=2013-01-05|archive-date=2013-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110055047/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-12-29-clark-nye-return_x.htm}}</ref> and was discontinued in 2022 in favor of a new special hosted from Miami by [[Miley_Cyrus|Miley Cyrus]] and [[Pete_Davidson|Pete Davidson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitovich|first1=Matt Webb|date=2021-11-29|title=Miley Cyrus and SNL's Pete Davidson to Host New Year's Eve Special for NBC|url=https://tvline.com/2021/11/29/miley-cyrus-pete-davidson-host-nbc-new-years-eve-special/|website=TVLine|access-date=2022-01-25|archive-date=2022-05-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220520223405/https://tvline.com/2021/11/29/miley-cyrus-pete-davidson-host-nbc-new-years-eve-special/}}</ref>

From 1956 to 1976, [[CBS|CBS]] televised [[Guy_Lombardo|Guy Lombardo]] and His Royal Canadians' annual New Year's Eve concert, most frequently from the [[Waldorf_Astoria_New_York|Waldorf-Astoria]]'s ballroom. It featured coverage from Times Square, and the band's signature rendition of "[[Auld_Lang_Syne|Auld Lang Syne]]" at midnight.<ref name=nbc-traditions/> After Lombardo's death in 1977, the special continued with Guy's younger brother [[Victor_Lombardo|Victor Lombardo]] as host and bandleader, but increasing competition from ABC's ''New Year’s Rockin’ Eve'' prompted CBS to replace it for 1979–80 with ''[[Happy_New_Year,_America|Happy New Year, America]]''. The new special ran in various formats with different hosts (such as [[Paul_Anka|Paul Anka]], [[Donny_Osmond|Donny Osmond]], [[Andy_Williams|Andy Williams]], [[Paul_Shaffer|Paul Shaffer]], and [[Montel_Williams|Montel Williams]]) until it was discontinued after 1996. Besides coverage during a special episode of ''[[Late_Show_with_David_Letterman|Late Show with David Letterman]]'' for 1999, and ''America's Millennium'' for 2000,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lynch |first=Stephen |title=New Year's song remains ingrained in public mind |url=http://www.augustachronicle.com/stories/123199/cy2_124-4983.shtml |newspaper=[[The_Orange_County_Register|The Orange County Register]] |date=1999-12-31 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050426133815/http://www.augustachronicle.com/stories/123199/cy2_124-4983.shtml |archive-date=2005-04-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Past, Present, and...Future?|date=2006-12-25|first=Scott|last=Collins|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=E1}}</ref><ref name="ppg-Lombardo">{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/tv/20011226guy1226p6.asp|title=Next week to be 25th New Year's Eve without Guy Lombardo|access-date=2007-01-01|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|first=Frazier|last=Moore|date=2001-12-26|agency=Associated Press|archive-date=2002-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020203151141/http://www.post-gazette.com/tv/20011226guy1226p6.asp}}</ref><ref name=ms-newguy>{{cite web|last=Terry|first=Carol Burton|title=New Guy Lombardo? Dick Clark sees New Year's tradition|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GntQAAAAIBAJ&pg=6190,6205752&dq=dick+clark's+new+year's+rockin+eve&hl=en|publisher=[[The_Milwaukee_Sentinel|The Milwaukee Sentinel]]|access-date=2012-12-19|archive-date=2015-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922135258/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GntQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fBIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6190%2C6205752&dq=dick+clark%27s+new+year%27s+rockin+eve&hl=en}}</ref> CBS did not air any national New Year's Eve programming until 2021, when it announced that it will carry a country music-themed special from Nashville for 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=2021-09-09|title=CBS Returns To New Year's Eve Live Programming With 'Nashville's Big Bash' Special Featuring Blake Shelton, Miranda Lambert, Brooks & Dunn & More|url=https://deadline.com/2021/09/cbs-new-years-eve-live-nashvilles-big-bash-special-blake-shelton-miranda-lambert-brooks-dunn-return-1234829475/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-09-10|website=Deadline|language=en-US|archive-date=2022-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220512191353/https://deadline.com/2021/09/cbs-new-years-eve-live-nashvilles-big-bash-special-blake-shelton-miranda-lambert-brooks-dunn-return-1234829475/}}</ref>

For 2000, in lieu of ''New Year's Rockin' Eve'', [[ABC_News|ABC News]] covered the festivities as part of its day-long telecast, ''[[ABC_2000_Today|ABC 2000 Today]]''. Hosted by then-chief correspondent [[Peter_Jennings|Peter Jennings]], the broadcast featured coverage of New Year's festivities from around the world as part of an [[2000_Today|international consortium]]. Dick Clark would join Jennings to co-anchor coverage from Times Square.<ref name=edr-dickclark>{{cite news|last=Bobbin|first=Jay|title=Dick Clark offers longer New Year's Eve special|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mygfAAAAIBAJ&pg=5437,5342253&dq=rockin+eve&hl=en|access-date=2012-04-20|newspaper=Ellensburg Daily Record|date=2000-12-28|archive-date=2022-06-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220611032253/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mygfAAAAIBAJ&pg=5437%2C5342253&dq=rockin+eve&hl=en}}</ref>

[[MTV|MTV]] had broadcast [[MTV_New_Year's|coverage]] originating from the network's Times Square studios at [[One_Astor_Plaza|One Astor Plaza]]. For 2011, MTV also held its own ball drop in [[Seaside_Heights,_New_Jersey|Seaside Heights, New Jersey]], the setting of its popular [[reality_television|reality]] series ''[[Jersey_Shore_(TV_series)|Jersey Shore]]'', featuring cast member [[Snooki|Snooki]] lowered inside a giant "[[hamster_ball|hamster ball]]". Originally, MTV planned to hold the drop within its studio in Times Square, but the network was asked by city officials to conduct the drop elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|title=Snooki 'dropped' from Times Square New Year's Eve celebration|url=http://www.silive.com/entertainment/tvfilm/index.ssf/2010/12/snooki_dropped_from_times_squa.html|access-date=2012-10-08|newspaper=[[Staten_Island_Advance|Staten Island Advance]]|date=2010-12-30|archive-date=2015-12-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223055459/http://www.silive.com/entertainment/tvfilm/index.ssf/2010/12/snooki_dropped_from_times_squa.html}}</ref>

For 2019, prominent [[Video_game_live_streaming|video game streamer]] [[Ninja_(video_game_player)|Ninja]] hosted a 12-hour New Year's Eve stream on [[Twitch_(service)|Twitch]] from Times Square, featuring matches of ''[[Fortnite_Battle_Royale|Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' with himself and special guests from a studio in the [[1501_Broadway|Paramount Building]]. Ninja made an on-stage appearance in Times Square during the festivities outside, which included a failed attempt to lead the crowd in a [[Floss_(dance)|floss]] dance (a routine made popular by ''Fortnite'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/26/18030602/fortnite-ninja-tyler-blevins-new-york-city-times-square-new-years-eve-red-bull-event|title=Fortnite star Ninja is getting his own 12-hour New Years Eve broadcast in Times Square|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2018-10-26|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-09-07|archive-date=2022-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220418183133/https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/26/18030602/fortnite-ninja-tyler-blevins-new-york-city-times-square-new-years-eve-red-bull-event}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/01/01/fortnites-ninja-new-years-floss-dance-fail/|title='Fortnite' Star Ninja's Attempt To Get Times Square To Do The Floss Dance Failed Miserably|website=Comicbook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07|archive-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310105119/https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/01/01/fortnites-ninja-new-years-floss-dance-fail/}}</ref>
